{"id":"2211.08357","submitter":"Thomas Rooijakkers","authors":"Sander Wiebing, Thomas Rooijakkers, Sebastiaan Tesink","title":"Improving AFL++ CmpLog: Tackling the bottlenecks","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The performance of the AFL++ CmpLog feature varies considerably for specific\nprograms under test (PUTs). In this paper it is demonstrated that the main\ncause of the poor performance is low seed entropy, and a lack of deduplication\nof magic bytes candidates. An improvement is proposed by mapping comparisons to\ninput bytes, in order to track which comparisons are controlled by what input\nbytes. This mapping is then used to fuzz only the comparison values that are\nmagic byte candidates for that input part. Second, a caching mechanism is\nintroduced to reduce the number of redundant executions. The evaluation of the\nimproved versions shows a significant coverage gain compared to the original\nAFL++ implementation of CmpLog for all PUTs, without breaking functionality.\nThe proposed solution in this paper provides a solid basis for a redesign of\nCmpLog.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 15 Nov 2022 18:05:48 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-16"}
